Inheritance with extends.

A class can extend another class. You write the keyword extends, then the name of the parent class. The class you extend is called the superclass. Your class is called the subclass. A subclass inherits every non private field and method of its superclass. It can add new ones, and it can override existing ones to change their behaviour.

In our example, the class Animal has a name field and a method called speak. The class Dog extends Animal. The Dog class inherits the name field for free. The Dog constructor calls super, the keyword that means call the superclass constructor, passing the name through. And the Dog class overrides the speak method so that when you call speak on a Dog instance, you get back the string rex barks instead of the generic version.

Three things to internalise here. First, the keyword extends establishes the parent child relationship. A class in Java can extend exactly one other class. There is no multiple inheritance of classes. Second, the call super open paren, arguments, close paren, calls the superclass constructor. It must be the first statement in the subclass constructor if you use it. Third, the annotation at sign Override. This is a built in annotation that you put on a method to declare that this method is meant to override one in the superclass. If the signature does not actually match, for example because you misspelled the method name, the compiler errors out instead of silently creating a new method that is unrelated to the parent. You should always use at sign Override on overriding methods. It catches a class of bugs that are otherwise very easy to miss.
